I have two main issues with the new behavior:
1. It does not support reproducible display, as the color will depend on the content of the data. If you want to compare two label images, they may end up with different colors for the same label. Not good for data analysis such as plotting a scatter plot and a label image side by side.
2. It is surprising: `label2rgb(label, colors=['yellow', 'red', 'blue'])` should do simple and predictable: 0 is yellow, 1 is red and so on. With `label2rgb(label, colors=['yellow', 'red', 'blue'], bg_label=0)`, this is just shifted: 1 is yellow, 2 is red... With the new behavior, it depends on the content of `label` image. Sure, we can always RTFM, but a lot of people are going to get bitten by that given the apparent simplicity of the API.

I propose the labels are simply wrapped around using _modulo indexing_, which is one way to perform color cycling. In previous example, label=3 and label=-3 would cycle back to yellow. I guess there could be a discussion on how bg_label=-1 should impact the negative labels exactly (I think bg_label=None should produce pure modulo indexing, whereas bg_label=-1 should shift all negative labels by 1). This approach is reproducible, follow least-surprise principle, and addresses the cases of negative labels as well as labels larger than the number of colors.

@stefanv Having non consecutive labels mapped to consecutive colors seems to me a complex scenario. I think in such case it is the responsibility of the user to opt-in for fancy relabeling behavior if modulo cycling is not enough for them rather than making the simple use cases convoluted. The option could be called `relabel_sequential=True` (direct mapping is simple->simple call, non sequential relabeling is complex->opt-in with one option)

@jni Thanks for the one liner. The power of label2rgb is that is both shows the intent of the programmer, and has a combination of functionalities such as bg_label/bg_color and automatic conversion from named color lists (see my example) that have no equivalent in pure NumPy. I would not ditch the 'reproducible mapping' as this quite a big issue for scientific applications of skimage.

@JDWarner, sorry for the delayed response.  I took a look at your fix today (which I see was already merged).  To my surprise, your change wasn't enough to fix the problem.

Or rather, there is actually a second problem.  You fixed the typo, but there is an additional exception that prevents the `_replace_by` function from working properly.  The tifffile code assumes that `_tifffile.so` can be found on `sys.path`.  Since `skimage.external.tifffile` is not on `sys.path`, the `_tifffile.so` module is not found.

I just pushed a PR (#1551) with a potential fix, but I'm not sure if it's a good idea to get out-of-sync with the original `tifffile` module.

